\section{Question 1}
see crudely stapled paper to the back of this assignment.

\section{Question 2.a}
The quark masses for $u,d,s$ are approximately the same in the limit compared to the baryons and mesons they compose ($m_u\approx m_d$ however $m_s$ has a greater difference between the two).

So we can consider them as a set of three particles only distinguishable by their label $u,d,s$. The strong force gluons don't see electric charge so even though the quarks have different charges, it remains a triplet of similar particles (The EM corrections are $\sim 1\%$ so we can neglect them).

This means there exists a symmetry between states composed with these three quarks which we can represent via the unitary transformation
\begin{align*}
  \m{u\\d\\s}\to U\m{u\\d\\s}
\end{align*}

i.e. We can mix states composed of $u,d$ and $s$ quarks and the resulting possible combinations are different kinds of the same particle up to the amount of $s$ quarks as the mass of $s$ is quite different. An example would be the meson octet which mixes the states $\ket{u\bar{u}},\ket{d\bar{d}}$ and $\ket{s\bar{s}}$.

\section{Question 2.b.i}
When we look at the $\Delta^{++}$ baryon for instance which has angular momentum $J=+\frac{3}{2}$ and in the ground state (quantum number $l=0$). $l=0\implies$ symmetric spatial wave function. The quark content to make this baryon must be $(uuu)$ to make the total charge so it's fully flavour symmetric (composed of all the same quarks).

However $u$ quarks are spin-$\frac{1}{2}$ fermions. By the Pauli exclusion principle we cannot have 2 fermions together with the same spin. We only have spin $\pm\frac{1}{2}$ for possible spins but we have 3 particles so 2 particles must have the same spin. So it should be impossible for a $(uuu)$ particle to exist but it does.

So we invent a new set of quantum numbers and call them colour. This gives us what is called $SU(3)$ colour symmetry in which we assign to every quark a colour or anti-colour (red, green, blue). If the total colour sums to white then the bound quark state is allowed.

This allows for the existence of the $\Delta^{++}$ baryon as it is colour neutral and all the quantum numbers of the particles aren't the same anymore.

\section{Question 2.b.ii}

The asymptotic freedom of the strong force ($SU(3)$ colour interactions) refers to the fact that the strong force gets asymptotically weaker at shorter distances/higher momentum transfers ($Q=-q$ where $q$ is the momentum transfer). When $Q$ is large, the coupling strength of the strong force is low which allows for us to only take lower order terms in a perturbative expansion.

The colour interactions become negligible and the electromagnetic force dominates. If the strong force is approximated as an exchange of pions, at high energies/short distances we can consider these exchanges of pions to be negligible.

\section{Question 2.b.iii}

A current quark refers to just the bare quark propagator through a true vacuum. However we know this is unrealistic so we refer to the constituent quark which is the current quark propagator dressed with gluon couplings and quark-antiquark loops interacting with the propagator. These gluons are self interacting and cause constant field fluctuations.

These constant gluon interactions or gluon dressing contribute to the effective mass. So in a sense this dressing dynamically creates mass which increases the mass of the bare quark propagator.

The current quark has only a small amount of mass compared to the constituent quark for the $u,d,s$ quarks so most the mass for these quarks comes from dynamically mass generation from gluon interactions.

The key reason why this occurs is that gluons carry colour themselves and we know that they interact with any coloured object. Our $SU(3)$ colour symmetry has assigned a colour to all quarks and in doing so has allowed them to interact with gluons. This allows for the gluon dressing of a quark propagator to occur and the end result is constant gluon self interacting and couplings to the coloured object i.e. the quark.

It is these couplings that dynamically create mass. Your mass does not come from the Higgs as two men named Derek once said.

