\section{Question 3.b}

We have mesons
\begin{align*}
  K^0=(\bar{s}d) \qquad \bar{K}^0=\qty(s\bar{d})
\end{align*}
Charge conjugation sends quarks to their anti-quarks so hence
\begin{align*}
  C\ket{K^0}=C\ket{\bar{s}d}=\ket{s\bar{d}}=\ket{\bar{K}^0}
\end{align*}
and similarly
\begin{align*}
  C\ket{\bar{K}^0}=\ket{K^0}
\end{align*}
The parity operator assigns a value of $+1$ for every particle and $-1$ for every anti-particle (this is done multiplicativly. Hence we have that
\begin{align*}
  P\ket{K^0}=P\ket{\bar{s}d}=(-1)(+1)\ket{\bar{s}d}=-\ket{K^0}
\end{align*}
similarly we have that
\begin{align*}
  P\ket{\bar{K}^0}=-\ket{\bar{K}^0}
\end{align*}

\section{Question 3.c}

Using the knowledge of the eigen-values from the previous question we can construct eigen states of $\ket{K^0}$ and $\ket{\bar{K}^0}$ which are just linear combinations of each other with an overall normalisation.

\begin{align*}
  \ket{K_1}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(\ket{K^0}-\ket{\bar{K}^0})\\
  \ket{K_2}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(\ket{K^0}+\ket{\bar{K}^0})
\end{align*}

Let's check if their eigen states of the $CP$ operator with some eigenvalues.

\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{K_1}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(CP\ket{K^0}-CP\ket{\bar{K}^0})\\
             &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(-\ket{\bar{K}^0}+\ket{K^0})\\
             &=(+1)\ket{K_1}
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{K_2}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(CP\ket{K^0}+CP\ket{\bar{K}^0})\\
             &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(-\ket{\bar{K}^0}-\ket{K^0})\\
             &=(-1)\ket{K_2}  
\end{align*}

Hence these are both eigen states of the $CP$ operator with eigen-value $\pm 1$.

\section{Question 3.d}

\begin{align*}
  \pi^0=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(u\bar{u}-d\bar{d})
\end{align*}
we have that
\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{\pi^0}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(CP\ket{u\bar{u}}-CP\ket{d\bar{d}})\\
               &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(-C\ket{u\bar{u}}+C\ket{d\bar{d}})\\
               &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\qty(-\ket{u\bar{u}}+\ket{d\bar{d}})\\
               &=-\ket{\pi^0}
\end{align*}
Using that $\ket{\pi^0}\otimes\ket{\pi^0}=\ket{\pi^0 \pi^0}$ as they are $\in L^2(\mathbb{C},m)$ with the Lebesgue measure $m$ (elements of an inner product space so the tensor product is well defined).

The parity operator will take $\vb{r}\to-\vb{r}$ for the spatial components. This will also give us the total angular momentum factor  $P\ket{l}\sim (-1)^l\ket{l}$ where $l$ is the angular momentum between the particles (assuming the particles are distinguishable). This comes from the spatial wave function.

If the particles aren't distinguishable then flipping the spatial vector $\vb{r}$ between them doesn't give us this factor as the particles essentially look like they're still in the same positions.

the $C$ operator will also have a factor of $(-1)^l$ for particles that are not their own anti-particle and not for ones that are via the same argument as above. When we swap particles for their anti-particle it reverses the direction but only if we can tell the difference between the particle and anti-particle. 

\begin{align*}
  \implies \ CP\ket{\pi^0\pi^0 l}&=(-1)(-1)\ket{\pi^0\pi^0 l}\\
                                 &=\ket{\pi^0\pi^0 l}
\end{align*}
so $\ket{\pi^0\pi^0 l}$ is an eigen-state of the $CP$ operator with eigenvalue $+1$.

Using the same process for the other state we get that
\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{\pi^+}&=CP\ket{u\bar{d}}\\
               &=-C\ket{u\bar{d}}\\
               &=-\ket{\bar{u}d}\\
               &=-\ket{\pi^{-}}\\
  CP\ket{\pi^-}&=CP\ket{\bar{u}d}\\
               &=-C\ket{\bar{u}d}\\
               &=-\ket{u\bar{d}}\\
               &=-\ket{\pi^+}
\end{align*}
here since the particles are not their own anti-particle and are distinguishable we get factors $(-1)^l$ for both $C$ and $P$ operators hence
\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{\pi^+\pi^-l}&=(-1)(-1)(-1)^l(-1)^l\ket{\pi^-\pi^+l}\\
                     &=(-1)^{2l}\ket{\pi^+\pi^-l}\\
                     &= \ket{\pi^+\pi^-l}
\end{align*}
as this is the same state of the two pion's together with angular momentum between them of $l$ and $l\in\mathbb{Z}$. So the state $\ket{\pi^+\pi^-l}$ is an eigen-state of the $CP$ operator with eigenvalue $+1$ as well.

\section{Question 3.e}

Using our previous knowledge of the $CP$ eigen-values we get that (Where to make it easier, we can consider these states constructed in the following way)
\begin{align*}
  \ket{\pi\pi\pi l_1l_2}=\ket{\pi\pi l_1}\otimes\ket{\pi\pi l_2}
\end{align*}
hence
\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{\pi^0\pi^0\pi^0l_1l_2}&=(-1)(-1)(-1)\\
                               &\phantom{=}\times(-1)^{l_2}\ket{\pi^0\pi^0\pi^0l_1l_2}\\
                               &=(-1)^{l_2+1}\ket{\pi^0\pi^0\pi^0l_1l_2}
\end{align*}
so $\ket{\pi^0\pi^0\pi^0l_1l_2}$ is an eigen-state of $CP$ with eigen-value $(-1)^{l_2+1}$.

\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{\pi^+\pi^-\pi^0l_1l_2}&=(-1)(-1)(-1)\\
  &\phantom{=}\times(-1)^{l_1}(-1)^{l_2}(-1)^{l_1}\ket{\pi^-\pi^+\pi^0l_1l_2}\\
                               &=(-1)^{2l_1+l_2+1}\ket{\pi^+\pi^-\pi^0l_1l_2}\\
                               &=(-1)^{l_2+1}\ket{\pi^+\pi^-\pi^0l_1l_2}
\end{align*}
Where a second factor of $(-1)^{l_2}$ does not come in as this is the angular momentum between $(\pi^+\pi^-)$ and $(\pi^0)$. So the $C$ operator on this combination does not pick up this factor. $\ket{\pi^+\pi^-\pi^0l_1l_2}$ is an eigen-state of the $CP$ operator with eigen-value $(-1)^{l_2+1}$.

If the original particle had spin-0 then by conservation of angular momentum, the total angular momentum of the final 3 particles must be 0 as well. Hence we have that
\begin{align*}
  l_1+l_2=J=0
\end{align*}
using the quantum number relation that if $J=0\implies j=0$ and that
\begin{align*}
  \abs{l_1-l_2}\leq j\leq l_1+l_2
\end{align*}

\section{Question 3.f}

if we let $l_1=l_2=0$ then both $CP$ eigen-states have eigen-value

\begin{align*}
  \text{e-value for both} = (-1)^{l_1+l_2+1}=(-1)
\end{align*}

So both states have $CP$ eigen-value $-1$.

\section{Question 3.g}

The first eigen-state is composed of only $\pi^0$'s which decay via the electromagnetic force through $\pi^0\to\gamma+\gamma$. It may not decay into a lepton and lepton neutrino pair as this would violate charge conservation.

The second state also has $\pi^\pm$ which may decay via the weak force through $\pi^+\to\mu^++\nu_\mu$ and $\pi^-\to\mu^-+\bar{\nu}_\mu$. The coupling strength of the weak interaction is much smaller then the coupling strength of the electromagnetic force.

Hence the first eigen-state which decays via the electromagnetic force has a much shorter life-time then the second eigenstate.

\section{Question 3.h}

Suppose we had two states
\begin{align*}
  \ket{K_1}=\ket{\pi\pi} \qquad \ket{K_2}=\ket{\pi\pi\pi}
\end{align*}
where in the first state we have $\pi^0\pi^0$ or $\pi^+\pi^-$ as our particles. Both compositions will produce a state with $CP$ eigen-value +1 which we have seen from part one.

The second state may have $\pi^0\pi^0\pi^0$ or $\pi^0\pi^-\pi^+$ as our particles. Both compositions will produce a state with $CP$ eigen-value -1 which we have seen from part one.

With these $CP$ eigen-states, we may now construct $K_L$ as a linear combination of these $CP$ eigen-states so it too will be a $CP$ eigen-state.

\begin{align*}
  \ket{K_L}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\abs{\epsilon}^2}}\qty(\ket{K_2}+\epsilon\ket{K_1})
\end{align*}

Due to the difference in the mean life times of the eigen-states, a long lived $K_L$ still contains a small amount of the $K_1$ eigen-state. If $CP$ was conserved, we would expect that this eigen-state would in the beginning have a $CP$ eigen-value of (suppose $\epsilon=1$ initially)

\begin{align*}
  CP\ket{K_L}\sim (+1-1)=0
\end{align*}

After a long experiment time you would expect the eigen-state $\ket{K_L}$ to only be composed of the $K_2$ so it should have a $CP$ eigen-value of -1. However we measure that the beam still has a small amount of the $K_1$ eigen-state, hence $CP$ is violated.






























































